node.text:
Grand Teton National Park has experienced many wonderful things this decade, thanks for spending the past 10 years with us! We cannot wait to see what the next decade brings.
#mygrandteton #findyourpark #encuentratuparque

node.title: Grand Teton National Park: A Look Over the Past Decade

node.text:
The mountains aren't disappearing - there's smoke in the air!

Smoke sensitive individuals and those with sensitive airways should take extra precautions when recreating outdoors. 

Learn more about current air quality at https://fire.airnow.gov.

#PlanLikeAParkRanger #TetonSafe 

NPS Photo/J. Bonney

node.text:
"Please don't take selfies with the fluffy cows!" The T shirt read.

Bison can move quickly when annoyed and do serious damage with those horns.  Stay at least 25 yards from bison and other animals, and 100 yards from bears and wolves.

But did you know these animals are the descendants of bison who were part of a wildlife park near Oxbow Bend? The wildlife park started in 1948. From it's beginning it drew controversy.

The wildlife park was soon disbanded. This was not before 15 bison escaped into the wild. The Teton's current 700+ bison herd are the descendants of those rebellious 15.

#MyGrandTeton

Contribution and Photo courtesy of/ L. Wilbanks
Taken with zoom lens

node.text:
Join us in celebrating the 31st anniversary of the Americans with Disability Act (ADA)! 

This important civil rights law ensures that everyone has equal rights and opportunities in all areas of public life, including access to national parks. While people with disabilities are the largest minority in the United States, their stories often remain untold.

Steve Arnold, a seasonal park ranger and veteran, has worked in national parks all over the country including Grand Teton, Yellowstone, Denali, Grand Canyon, Bryce Canyon, and Glacier. He is also a professor of instructional technology at the University of Arizona. Steve has been a wheelchair user for about 30 years. To him, the ADA means that all people of differing abilities have the possibility to enjoy the same aspects of life. 

The 1872 legislation that created Yellowstone, the world’s first national park, included a powerful statement, “For the Benefit and Enjoyment of the People.” As Shelton Johnson says in Ken Burns’ “National Parks: America's Best Idea” documentary, this legislation refers to ALL of the people, not just SOME of the people. Steve has taken that statement to heart from an accessibility standpoint.

In 1994, Steve first started with the National Park Service to conduct accessibility analyses of the parks. He encountered resistant attitudes towards accessibility improvements in parks. Some people believe that the founding principles of the NPS, to “preserve and protect unimpaired” doesn’t allow for ADA exceptions. He has since experienced improvements in accessibility and attitudes across the national parks, including the Jenny Lake redesign in Grand Teton. However, he pointed out the ongoing need for more accessible trails beyond the road system in parks, where people of all abilities can feel immersed in nature. 

That is what the ADA is all about: making places accessible to all people. The National Park Service is making strides toward a more accessible future with a strategic plan for improving accessibility and renewed commitment to the ADA.

#ADA31 #ThanksToTheADA #MyGrandTeton

Photo courtesy of S. Textor

node.text:
Back in it’s heyday… 

The Bar BC was once one of the most famous dude ranches in the American West. Today, it contains many of the original structures during its period of significance.

The serentiy of the ranch along the picturesque Snake River provided inspiration for well known writers and poets, including William Faulkner and Ernest Hemingway. Some guests even arrived with their type writers.

Struthers Burt, owner of Bar BC and a popular author himself, used his power of pen to advocate for the scenic qualities of Grand Teton National Park.

Imagine getting the chance to stay at the historic Bar BC. What would you inspire to write about?

Photo courtesy of M.Duff

#MyGrandTeton

node.text:
Granite Canyon has incredible plants, scenery, and geological formations. The only thing this canyon is missing is it's own namesake: Granite. Early explorers misidentified the rocks found around the upper canyons as granite. These rocks are actually metamorphosed gabbro, otherwise known as metagabbro.

Check out the full-sized image on our Facebook page!

#FindYourPark #MyGrandTeton #EncuentraTuParque 

Photo courtesy of E.Kim

node.text:
Step aside butterflies, it’s time for another National Moth Week feature! Check out this photogenic sagebrush sheep moth (Hemileuca hera) who sure wasn’t sheepish in front of our camera. 

You can catch these striking beauties flying during the day across the sagebrush steppe from July to September. Their thick black markings on large, pure-white wings are a dead giveaway that makes misidentification unlikely. 

Yet another species that relies on the steppe for survival, sagebrush sheep moth larvae are food specialists which will only eat a select few types of sagebrush and wildflowers as they mature. Like other Saturniid moths, the adults don’t feed at all and instead rely on fat reserves gained from munching sagebrush when young. Fun fact: To avoid getting eaten, the caterpillars are covered in needle-like spines that can inject a stinging toxin, so don’t touch! 

Because of their deep reliance on the sagebrush steppe ecosystem, some ecologists consider the presence of these moths to be an indicator of high-quality steppe habitat for wildlife. 

#secretsofthesage #nationalmothweek #sagebrushsteppe #MothWeek 

Photo courtesy of S. Wessel

node.text:
Grand Teton National Park is home to six morainal lakes and over 100 alpine and backcountry lakes. Most of these lakes were formed when glaciers carved through the land and then filled the depression with snowmelt. Some alpine lakes will appear turquoise or milky white due to the presence of silt-sized sediments of feldspar and quartz grinded through erosion. Come explore some of these incredible lakes!

Check out the full size image on our Facebook page!

#MyGrandTeton #FindYourPark #EncuentraTuParque 

Photo Courtesy of E.Kim

node.text:
Where will you be when the full moon rises tonight?

In the U.S., this July's full moon is the “Buck Moon”, named for the time of year when the fuzzy antlers of buck deer are growing. It is also known as the “Thunder Moon” because of frequent thunderstorms during the month of July. 

In Grand Teton, the full moon rises tonight just after sunset at 9:14 pm MST. Find a high, east-facing view in the park to enjoy the show!

Wherever you are, look up your local lunar calendar to plan full moon viewing!

#MyGrandTeton #FindYourPark #EncuentraTuParque

Photo courtesy of S. Textor

node.text:
Please do not eat the flowers!!

Well, unless you are a moose.

There is so much to see in Grand Teton National Park! The wildflowers and trees are an important part of that resource. 

Watching the animals of the park forage is such a great reward for our visitors so it is O.K. if they eat the flowers.

#donoteattheflowers #findyourpark #MyGrandTeton 

Photo Courtesy of/ BK Appleby

node.text:
Meet the Blinded sphinx moth (Paonias Excaecatus)!

Despite the name, blinded sphinx moths aren't actually blind. Many moths and butterflies have eyespots, which are circles of rich color usually centered around a black dot which mimics a pupil. The blinded sphinx has an eyespot, but no pupil dot. If a human eye lacked a pupil, vision would be unlikely, hence the name. The blinded sphinx have eyes on their head and can see fine.

Like the cecropia moth, blinded sphinx adults don't eat and use all of their energy to reproduce.

#MothWeek #MyGrandTeton 

NPS Photo/J. Bonney

node.text:
Welcome to #WildflowerWednesday! 

Here are some of the beautiful wildflowers from throughout Grand Teton National Park. In turn you might have some of your own favorite wildflower/s where you live, to share.  Be sure to contribute your favorite wildflower photos too!

This week’s Grand Teton National Park wildflower, the Colorado Columbine. -  Aquilegia alpine - it is a hardy perennial wildflower, a member of the Buttercup family. They are native to forests, mountain meadows, and alpine slopes. The columbine grows up to 3 feet in height. Their blooms resemble jester's caps and the spurs resemble the talons of an eagle. 

Columbines and other wildflowers are fragile. Please do not pick them in the park. The impact from wildflower picking begins a critical chain of events which includes the loss to the future visitors and loss of seeds to ensure the next season's blooms. Wildflowers also support ecosystems for pollinators, birds, and small animals. Insects and animals depend on seeds, nectar, and pollen for their food supply.

Do you have any columbines in your own garden or photos to share?

#MyGrandTeton 

Photo Courtesy of BK Appleby
